<br>
...and some of the pretty desktop enhancements like transparency and shading by opening your System Properties, Advanced, Performance Options, and turning off some of the stuff listed there.<br>
<br>
Lastly, you might consider getting a *slightly* newer video card (pretty much anything beyond TNT2), since the TNT2 relies pretty heavily on the CPU to perform calculations.  I'm a little hesitant to suggest a GeForce card, due to problems with recent drivers and Via-based motherboards, but anything that supports hardware T&amp;L should greatly improve performance in games that use that (such as EQ).  The vid card does the work and leaves more CPU time for more important things, like making you breakfast.  I'd try using system tweaks first, though.<br>
<br>
ALSO, be sure to back up your system settings before tweaking (Start, Programs, Accessories, System Tools, System Restore, Create a Restore Point.)  That way you can roll back any changes you made without having to go back a day or two in the registry. <p><img src="http://home.swbell.net/sdspies/images/caederesig.jpg" BORDER="0" WIDTH="216"
